		 Tuesday, April 20, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	New Delhi: Two Indian wrestlers have won silver medals at the senior Asian freestyle wrestling championship held in Teheran.				 																																	Sujeet Maan (74kg) and Palwinder Singh Cheema (120kg) won the medals in the competition that concluded in the Iranian capital on Sunday, a Wrestling Federation of India press release said on Monday.				 																																	Another Indian wrestler, Ramesh Kumar, competing in the 66kg category, finished fourth in the championships, the release added. 				 																																	Durban: The widow of former South African cricket captain Hansie Cronje is to marry again, according to local media reports.				 																																	Bertha Cronje has found new love in Jacques du Plessis who lives in the town of George in the Western Cape province, according to the Johannesburg based Rapport newspaper works as an auditor.				 																																	Cronje died in a plane crash two years ago. 				 																																	Bertha told the newspaper that she shared the same spiritual values as Du Plessis. I met him slightly less than a year ago. Since then our friendship has blossomed into something beautiful and precious,se said.				 																																	Cronjes elder brother, Frans Cronje, told Cape Times that the Cronje family is extremely happy for her. 				 																																	Seoul: South Korea coach Humberto Coelho said on Monday he had reached an agreement with the Korea Football Association (KFA) to step down from his position. Under pressure since the scoreless draw against the Maldives in a World Cup qualifier, Coelho said he would leave South Korea on Tuesday. I am very sorry that I could not finish my term, he said. 				 																																	Brussels: World No. 1 Justine Henin-Hardenne is suffering from a virus and will be out of action for the next two weeks.				 																																	Im suffering from a virus similar to glandular fever, Henin-Hardenne said on her website. Despite the rest Im taking now for the next two weeks, Im reassured about my health. In two weeks, I will know a lot more about the virus.				 																																	The 21-year-old Belgian withdrew from the Family Circle Cup in Charleston last Tuesday saying that low blood sugar was causing light headedness. 				 																																	Monaco: Top seed Andy Roddick has pulled out of this weeks Monte Carlo Masters, organisers said on Monday.				 																																	The American, who lost in the US Clay Court final to Germanys Tommy Haas on Sunday, withdrew for non-medical reasons.				 																																	Meanwhile, Goran Ivanisevics glory days looked far behind him on Monday when he was beaten in the first round by French qualifier Nicolas Devilder 6-4, 2-6, 2-6. Ivanisevic was playing his sixth tournament of the year and he has won just two matches in 2004.				 																																	Sheffield: Joe Swail put last years losing finalist Ken Doherty out of the world championship in the first round at the Crucible Theatre on Sunday. With an overnight lead of 5-4, Northern Irishman Swail went on to complete a 10-5 victory over the 1997 champion.World No. 9 Matthew Stevens beat Thailands James Wattana 10-7. Sport on Screen Cricket: Sri Lanka vs Zimbabwe, first ODI live from 12.50 pm on ESPN
